different types of conductive patterns were designed on the surface of photographic paper through a graphite ink rollerball pen. As showed in Fig. 1
                        , various conducting patterns, a 3.0 V battery and a dip LED with a rated voltage of 3.0 V were fabricated on paper substrate. Cathode surface of battery attached to one side of conductive pattern and one of the LED legs (cathode) connected to battery anode. When the LED anode leg touched to other side of conductive pattern, the electronic circuit switched on and the LED lighted up. Subsequently, the resistance of conductive patterns measured by ohmmeter. Also, the conductivity of graphite ink was 93.6 μs. With 90° bending outwards, the reliability and flexibility of conductive patterns were evaluated (Fig. 1, and Table 1
                        ).

Concerning to CVs, the redox peak of bare GCE was increased after the modification of the electrode by the graphite ink. This result shows that the graphite ink matrix with its conductivity and proper structure is capable to effectively increment of the electron transfer rate of the [Fe(CN)6]3−/4- solution. In the next step, after incubation of modified GCE with the graphite ink containing EDC/NHS as organic activators and anti-CA 15–3 antibody, the peak current was decreased. Blocking the electrode surface by anti-CA 15–3 antibody/graphite bioink reduces the efficiency of the electron exchange from the supporting electrolyte, and slow down the kinetics of electron transfer. It can be concluded that the anti CA15–3 antibody/graphite bioink has been successfully immobilized at the modified GCE surface. Due to poor conductivity of electrode, the electron transfer occurs at a lower rate. But, following the BSA blocking an increase on the peak currents was observed. While, after incubation with blocking agent BSA, the redox peak has been increase compared to the GCE modified by anti CA15–3 antibody/graphite bioink. Also, after CA 15–3 antigen (Ag) incubation, the redox peak has been increased again in comparison to the previous step, which indicates the formation of the antibody-antigen complex successfully happened. The results obtained from the sensitive DPV, SWV and ChA techniques confirm the successful immobilization of biological components on the modified electrode surface (Fig. 4
                        ) (Fig. 5
                        ).
